verses.text: And it came to pass after these things , \add that\add* the butler of the king of Egypt and \add his\add* baker had offended their lord the king of Egypt.
And Pharaoh was wroth against two \add of\add* his officers , against the chief of the butlers , and against the chief of the bakers.
And he put them in ward in the house of the captain of the guard , into the prison , the place where Joseph \add was\add* bound.
And the captain of the guard charged Joseph with them, and he served them: and they continued a season in ward. \p

¶ And they dreamed a dream both of them , each man his dream in one night , each man according to the interpretation of his dream , the butler and the baker of the king of Egypt , which \add were\add* bound in the prison.
And Joseph came in unto them in the morning , and looked upon them, and, behold, they \add were\add* sad.

And he asked Pharaoh’s officers that \add were\add* with him in the ward of his lord’s house , saying , Wherefore look ye \add so\add* sadly to day ?\f + \fr 40.7 \ft look…: Heb. are your faces evil?\f*

And they said unto him, We have dreamed a dream , and \add there is\add* no interpreter of it. And Joseph said unto them, \add Do\add* not interpretations \add belong\add* to God ? tell me \add them\add*, I pray you.
And the chief butler told his dream to Joseph , and said to him, In my dream , behold, a vine \add was\add* before me ;
And in the vine \add were\add* three branches : and it \add was\add* as though it budded , \add and\add* her blossoms shot forth ; and the clusters thereof brought forth ripe grapes :
And Pharaoh’s cup \add was\add* in my hand : and I took the grapes , and pressed them into Pharaoh’s cup , and I gave the cup into Pharaoh’s hand.
And Joseph said unto him, This \add is\add* the interpretation of it: The three branches \add are\add* three days :

Yet within three days shall Pharaoh lift up thine head , and restore thee unto thy place : and thou shalt deliver Pharaoh’s cup into his hand , after the former manner when thou wast his butler.\f + \fr 40.13 \ft lift…: or, reckon\f*

But think on me when it shall be well with thee, and shew kindness , I pray thee, unto me, and make mention of me unto Pharaoh , and bring me out of this house :\f + \fr 40.14 \ft think…: Heb. remember me with thee\f*
For indeed I was stolen away out of the land of the Hebrews : and here also have I done nothing that they should put me into the dungeon.

When the chief baker saw that the interpretation was good , he said unto Joseph , I also \add was\add* in my dream , and, behold, \add I had\add* three white baskets on my head :\f + \fr 40.16 \ft white: or, full of holes\f*

And in the uppermost basket \add there was\add* of all manner of bakemeats for Pharaoh ; and the birds did eat them out of the basket upon my head.\f + \fr 40.17 \ft bakemeats…: Heb. meat of Pharaoh, the work of a baker, or, cook\f*
And Joseph answered and said , This \add is\add* the interpretation thereof: The three baskets \add are\add* three days :

Yet within three days shall Pharaoh lift up thy head from off thee, and shall hang thee on a tree ; and the birds shall eat thy flesh from off thee.\f + \fr 40.19 \ft lift…: or, reckon thee, and take thy office from thee\f* \p

¶ And it came to pass the third day , \add which was\add* Pharaoh’s birthday , that he made a feast unto all his servants : and he lifted up the head of the chief butler and of the chief baker among his servants.\f + \fr 40.20 \ft lifted…: or, reckoned\f*
And he restored the chief butler unto his butlership again ; and he gave the cup into Pharaoh’s hand :
But he hanged the chief baker : as Joseph had interpreted to them.
Yet did not the chief butler remember Joseph , but forgat him.
